<p style="text-align:justify;">comb and scarcely reaches the neck, sticks clotted together something like the mane of a Colt when it begins to fall off<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  With matrons stumps commonly take place of fingers &#8211; the nails and the first joints of their fingers they tear off through grief, or rather through custom at the death of relations.  Young women are often pleased against their will &#8211; the Young men never take a refusal &#8211; but often beat them into consent &#8211; and both parties must keep the secret at the risk of their lives.  On these occasions the young people are not very delicate especially when sure of secrecy &#8211; for they think it no ways inconvenient to go through their amorous engagements in the presence of women and Frenchmen<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This Tribe has a great deal of what they call <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Hazal</span> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Gidda</span> or stinking pride.</p>
